<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05016h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05016h">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05016h"> 16(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> emerods</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"> But this <font color="green">[assault on Dagon]</font> did not suffice. Old Jahveh&apos;s blood was up. He smote the men of Ashdod with <mark>emerods</mark>. The most superficial readers of the Bible, when they remember what a dirty victory the Lord gained over the magicians of Egypt, will readily conceive that this was a very filthy disorder. It was the bleeding piles or worse. Perhaps the sweet Psalmist had this incident in mind when he sang that the Lord &ldquo;smote his enemies in the hinder-parts; he put them to a perpetual reproach.&rdquo; <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [A God in a Box] 123</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
